<p>Grand Island's cold climate requires robust heating systems capable of maintaining comfort during harsh Nebraska winters with temperatures often dropping below zero. For this climate zone, high-efficiency gas furnaces with AFUE ratings of 90% or higher are typically the most cost-effective primary heating option, though heat pumps are becoming viable with newer cold-climate models rated for sub-zero operation. Air conditioning needs are moderate, making SEER ratings of 14-16 appropriate for most homes, though higher SEER ratings provide better comfort and efficiency during Grand Island's humid summer months.</p>

